⁠
Are you using this approach?⁠
⁠
It’s a very simple way to set up your diet and is something I personally use. Aim for at least 80% of your calories coming from whole foods and minimally processed foods. So what does that mean?⁠
⁠
Firstly foods like⁠
Legumes⁠
Whole grain⁠
Nuts⁠
Seeds⁠
Fruit⁠
Veg⁠
Herbs & Spices⁠
⁠
Plus minimally processed foods like red lentil pasta, nut butter made from 100% nuts, tempeh, tofu, bean burgers etc.⁠
⁠
While 20% of your calories or less can come from more processed foods like meat alternatives like @beyondmeat, chocolate, vegan cheese etc.⁠
⁠
So what are the benefits of this? The majority of your diet will come from nutrient-dense foods with more fiber, vitamins, minerals etc, but still, have a place for some other foods that you enjoy.⁠
⁠
Obviously these are just guidelines and some foods can be on either side depending on how it’s made, so you’ll have to use your best judgment on certain foods.⁠
⁠
Hope this helps!⁠

